<br>
One thing I noticed, skills and feats help make all stats play an important role in the game.  In previous editions of D&amp;D, charisma, intelligence and wisdom were pretty much pointless for a fighter.  However, they now play a bigger part.  For example, a fighter's intelligence dictates how many more skills a fighter can learn as he levels. <br>
<br>
Skills and feats may at first appear to be minor details, but I've quickly learned just how vital they can be.  An average character can become an amazing one just by choosing the right skills and feats when he's first created...and as he levels.<br>
<br>
Choosing equipment really helps shape your character as well.  You can't carry or afford everything as you start out.  This is especially true for the lighter armored classes since they need to keep their encumbrance very low to remain at peak combat efficiency.<br>
<br>
So yes, the best way to become an expert in AD&amp;D 3rd Edition rules is to use them in a game.   Reading them is one thing.  Applying them to a game where players frequently do unexpected things is quite another.<br>
<br>
--Robert<br>
