"Lead, follow or get out of the way"</font></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#97694F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub26.ezboard.com/uamberyllarydunmorn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Amberyll Arydunmorn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 996<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(6/23/01 5:28:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub26.ezboard.com/fapex71990frm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=51.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Which AD&amp;D class/race do you like to play?</span><hr size=1> Well, i had always liked to play spell casters, whether they be magic users or clerics.  Never druids though, i always thought them to be useless treehuggers and laughed at them being a major class when EQ came out (little did i know the power of the farmer...).<br>
<br>
My favorite types of casters were ones that used their talents in not-so-straightforward ways.  I was not one of the good wizards that sat in the back with lightning bolt and fire ball memorized and nuked anything that approched that might be thinking to attack us.  I was also someone who believed magic should NOT be easily mastered, and mistakes should be often occurances in the arts for anyone other than the upmost highest level magic users (clerics were different, their talents came as gifts from their gods).  Because of this, i LOVED the addition of the 'wild mage' speciliazation, in which strange magics would occur when you least expect them.  When unable to play a character like this, i would simply use 'creative magics' in order to try to accomplish tasks as opposed to brute force.  Although illusions were not my speciality, i liked to tinker in other realms.<br>
<br>
Apart from this type of character, my favorite char was a multiclass mage-assassin.  Instead of using my magical talents in order to highlight my theiving abilities, i used my abilities of stealth and hand speed to try to enhance (or rather acquire) new magical components in order to do more precise damage (assassinate) to a victim.  It was sometimes difficult to separate out and explain to the group why id not just randomly steal from passterbyes, being a theif and all, but a guy has to have his morals, even if they are considered a hired killer.<br>
<br>
The third type of char i dabbled in was Psionicists - but they were way too hard for GMs to understand and / or control, especially at lower levels, and therefore were not very viable in normal campaignes.<br>
<br>
I never played tanks, and do not think i will in NWN either.  I just like to have more things to play with than just a few swords and a cool bow =)<br>
<br>
